It appears to me that this apparently unimportant question is not obscurely connected with the larger question whether the Olassics are still to form the staple of higher education amongst us If their claim to do so is to be allowed, they must show good reasons for it, and they must at the same time leave room for other more immediately pressing studies I believe that this claim will bc allowed in so far as the study of the Classica supplies the necessary instrument for entering into the life aud thought of the ancient world, and one of the best instrumente for learning the laws which regulate the expression of thought But the Universities will have to see to it that this is done far more thoroughly than it has yet been done; and for this purpose it will be necessary to drop some of the impedimenta, which now oceupy the time of the learner without tending‚ in any correspondiug degree, to discipline and seed the mind. Yet, ot late years, it seems to me that the burden of the impedimenta has been added to rather than reduced hythe new importance which has been given to questions of etymology and orthography.
